{
  "What physical properties can spectroscopy reveal about a celestial object?": "",
  "Only its color and brightness": "",
  "Only its distance from Earth": "",
  "Chemical composition, temperature, density, velocity, and magnetic field": "",
  "Only its shape and size": "",
  "Spectroscopy is one of the most powerful tools in astronomy because it can extract a wide range of physical information from light, including an object's chemical composition, temperature, density, radial velocity, and magnetic field strength.": "",
  "How are absorption lines produced in a spectrum?": "",
  "Magnetic fields bend light into discrete lines": "",
  "Cooler gas absorbs specific wavelengths from a continuous background source": "",
  "Hot, dense gas emits light at all wavelengths": "",
  "Stars reflect light off nearby planets": "",
  "According to Kirchhoff's second law, absorption lines appear when cooler, low-density gas sits between a continuous light source and the observer, absorbing photons at specific wavelengths corresponding to its atomic energy transitions.": "",
  "How are emission lines produced in a spectrum?": "",
  "Gravity compresses light into narrow bands": "",
  "Cool gas absorbs light and re-emits it as a continuous spectrum": "",
  "A hot, low-density gas emits light at specific wavelengths characteristic of its elements": "",
  "Dense solid objects glow at specific wavelengths": "",
  "Kirchhoff's third law states that a hot, low-density gas emits light at specific discrete wavelengths determined by the energy level transitions of the atoms present, producing a bright-line or emission spectrum.": "",
  "Why does each chemical element produce a unique pattern of spectral lines?": "",
  "Spectral lines are assigned randomly by astronomers": "",
  "Only hydrogen produces spectral lines": "",
  "Each element has a unique electron configuration that produces unique energy level transitions": "",
  "All elements share the same electron structure": "",
  "Each element has a distinct arrangement of electrons occupying specific energy levels, so the photons emitted or absorbed during transitions between these levels have unique wavelengths, creating a spectral fingerprint that identifies the element.": "",
  "Where was helium first discovered?": "",
  "In the Sun's spectrum during the 1868 solar eclipse, before it was found on Earth": "",
  "In a meteorite sample": "",
  "In a chemistry laboratory on Earth": "",
  "In the spectrum of the Moon": "",
  "Helium was first identified as an unknown spectral line in the Sun's chromosphere during the 1868 solar eclipse by Jules Janssen and Norman Lockyer, and it was named after the Greek word 'Helios' meaning Sun, since it was not found on Earth until nearly three decades later.": "",
  "What does a Doppler blueshift in a star's spectral lines indicate?": "",
  "The star is approaching the observer, compressing wavelengths to shorter, bluer values": "",
  "The star is stationary but very hot": "",
  "The star is rotating but not moving toward or away from us": "",
  "The star is moving away from the observer": "",
  "When a light source moves toward an observer, the observed wavelengths are compressed to shorter (bluer) values due to the Doppler effect, so a blueshift in spectral lines indicates the object is approaching.": "",
  "What does a Doppler redshift in a star's spectral lines indicate?": "",
  "The star is very hot and emitting red light": "",
  "The star has no radial velocity": "",
  "The star is approaching the observer": "",
  "The star is receding from the observer, stretching wavelengths to longer, redder values": "",
  "When a light source moves away from an observer, the observed wavelengths are stretched to longer (redder) values due to the Doppler effect, so a redshift indicates the object is receding.": "",
  "What does Wien's displacement law relate?": "",
  "The peak wavelength of a blackbody's emission to its temperature, with hotter objects peaking at shorter wavelengths": "",
  "A star's luminosity to its distance when considering all relevant factors": "",
  "The speed of light to gravitational strength within the typical range of values": "",
  "A star's mass to its radius, particularly regarding emission in the context of this analysis": "",
  "Wien's displacement law states that the peak wavelength of a blackbody's emission is inversely proportional to its temperature (lambda_max = b/T), meaning hotter objects radiate most intensely at shorter wavelengths.": "",
  "How can a star's surface temperature be determined?": "",
  "By counting the number of planets orbiting it": "",
  "By weighing the star on a scale": "",
  "By measuring its distance with a ruler": "",
  "By analyzing its spectrum using the peak wavelength from Wien's law or spectral line ratios": "",
  "A star's surface temperature can be determined from its spectrum by identifying the wavelength at which it emits most intensely (Wien's law) or by comparing the relative strengths of spectral lines, since different ionization states dominate at different temperatures.": "",
  "The stellar classification sequence OBAFGKM is based on what property?": "",
  "Mass of the star, heaviest to lightest": "",
  "Spectral characteristics reflecting surface temperature, from hottest (O, ~30,000+ K) to coolest (M, ~3,000 K)": "",
  "Distance from Earth, nearest to farthest": "",
  "Age of the star, youngest to oldest": "",
  "The OBAFGKM sequence classifies stars by their spectral characteristics, which directly reflect surface temperature, ranging from the hottest O-type stars at over 30,000 K to the coolest M-type stars at around 3,000 K. The mnemonic 'Oh Be A Fine Girl/Guy Kiss Me' helps students remember the order.": "",
  "What is spectroscopy?": "",
  "The study of how gravity affects the motion of celestial bodies": "",
  "The study of how telescopes magnify images of distant objects": "",
  "The study of the interaction between matter and electromagnetic radiation, involving the analysis of light split into its component wavelengths": "",
  "The measurement of star positions to determine parallax distances": "",
  "Spectroscopy is the branch of science concerned with the investigation and measurement of spectra produced when matter interacts with or emits electromagnetic radiation, allowing astronomers to determine the composition, temperature, and motion of celestial objects.": "",
  "What is a continuous spectrum?": "",
  "An unbroken band of colors or wavelengths emitted by a hot, dense object such as a star's core or a heated solid": "",
  "A spectrum that contains dark absorption lines at specific wavelengths": "",
  "A spectrum showing only a few isolated bright lines against a dark background": "",
  "A spectrum that only contains ultraviolet and infrared light": "",
  "A continuous spectrum is an unbroken distribution of light across all wavelengths, produced by a hot, dense object like a star's photosphere or an incandescent bulb. Kirchhoff's first law states that a hot, dense gas or solid emits a continuous spectrum.": "",
  "What is the Zeeman effect?": "",
  "The splitting of spectral lines into multiple components in the presence of a strong magnetic field": "",
  "The broadening of spectral lines caused by high temperature in a gas": "",
  "The disappearance of spectral lines at extremely high pressures": "",
  "The shift of spectral lines caused by an object's radial velocity": "",
  "The Zeeman effect is the splitting of a spectral line into several components when the light source is in the presence of a magnetic field. Astronomers use this effect to measure the strength and orientation of magnetic fields in sunspots, stars, and other astrophysical environments.": "",
  "What is cosmological redshift?": "",
  "A redshift caused by gravitational lensing near massive objects": "",
  "A reddening of starlight caused by interstellar dust scattering blue wavelengths": "",
  "The stretching of light wavelengths caused by the expansion of space itself as light travels across the universe": "",
  "A redshift caused by a star's own motion through space away from the observer": "",
  "Cosmological redshift is distinct from Doppler redshift because it is not caused by an object's motion through space; instead, the fabric of space itself expands while light is in transit, stretching the photon's wavelength to longer, redder values over cosmic distances.": "",
  "What does spectral line broadening mean?": "",
  "The total number of spectral lines visible in a spectrum increases": "",
  "Spectral lines shift from one color to another over time": "",
  "Spectral lines disappear entirely at high temperatures": "",
  "Spectral lines become wider than their natural width due to physical effects such as temperature, pressure, rotation, or magnetic fields": "",
  "Spectral line broadening refers to the widening of spectral lines beyond their natural, intrinsic width. It can be caused by thermal motion (thermal broadening), high pressure (pressure broadening), rapid rotation (rotational broadening), or strong magnetic fields (Zeeman broadening), and astronomers use it to infer physical conditions.": "",
  "What is the Balmer series?": "",
  "The set of hydrogen emission or absorption lines in the visible spectrum caused by electron transitions to or from the second energy level": "",
  "A classification system for star brightness based on apparent magnitude": "",
  "A group of infrared spectral lines produced by water molecules in stellar atmospheres": "",
  "A series of spectral lines produced by helium atoms in the ultraviolet range": "",
  "The Balmer series consists of the hydrogen spectral lines that result from electron transitions to or from the n=2 energy level, producing lines in the visible spectrum (such as H-alpha at 656 nm, H-beta at 486 nm). Because hydrogen is the most abundant element, these lines are fundamental in astronomical spectroscopy.": "",
  "What is a spectrograph?": "",
  "A type of radio antenna used to detect microwave radiation": "",
  "A camera that takes wide-field images of the night sky": "",
  "A device that measures the total brightness of a star without separating wavelengths": "",
  "An instrument that disperses incoming light into its component wavelengths and records the resulting spectrum for analysis": "",
  "A spectrograph is an instrument attached to a telescope that uses a prism, diffraction grating, or other dispersive element to spread light into its component wavelengths and record the resulting spectrum. Modern spectrographs can achieve extremely high resolution, detecting stellar wobbles as small as 1 m/s for exoplanet detection.": "",
  "What does Kirchhoff's laws of spectroscopy describe?": "",
  "The orbital mechanics of binary star systems": "",
  "The relationship between a star's mass and its luminosity": "",
  "The three conditions under which continuous, emission, and absorption spectra are produced": "",
  "How electric circuits distribute current and voltage": "",
  "Kirchhoff's three laws of spectroscopy describe the conditions that produce each type of spectrum: a hot, dense object produces a continuous spectrum; a hot, low-density gas produces an emission line spectrum; and a cooler gas in front of a continuous source produces an absorption line spectrum.": "",
  "What is transit spectroscopy?": "",
  "A technique that compares a star's spectrum during and outside of a planetary transit to detect absorption features from the planet's atmosphere": "",
  "Using spectroscopy to track the transit times of satellites across the Sun": "",
  "Measuring the brightness dip when a planet crosses in front of its star to determine the planet's size": "",
  "Analyzing the spectrum of a planet by landing a probe on its surface": "",
  "Transit spectroscopy works by comparing a star's spectrum when a planet is transiting in front of it versus when it is not; the difference reveals absorption or emission features imprinted by the planet's atmosphere. The James Webb Space Telescope (JWST) excels at this technique, enabling detection of molecules like water and carbon dioxide in exoplanet atmospheres.": "",
  "What does the Doppler formula (change in wavelength / wavelength = velocity / speed of light) mean in spectroscopy?": "",
  "It relates the fractional shift in a spectral line's wavelength to the radial velocity of the source along the line of sight": "",
  "It determines how far away a star is based on its apparent brightness": "",
  "It measures the total luminosity of a star based on its color": "",
  "It calculates the chemical composition of a star from the number of spectral lines observed": "",
  "The Doppler formula relates the observed wavelength shift of spectral lines to the radial velocity of the source. By measuring how much a known spectral line has shifted from its rest wavelength, astronomers can calculate whether the object is approaching or receding and at what speed.": "",
  "An astronomer observes that all of a distant galaxy's spectral lines are shifted to longer wavelengths compared to laboratory reference values. What can the astronomer conclude about this galaxy?": "",
  "The galaxy is surrounded by unusually hot gas that distorts the spectrum": "",
  "The galaxy is receding from us, as the redshift indicates motion away from the observer": "",
  "The galaxy is moving toward Earth at high speed": "",
  "The galaxy is rotating rapidly but not moving toward or away from us": "",
  "A uniform shift of all spectral lines to longer (redder) wavelengths is the hallmark of Doppler redshift, indicating the galaxy is moving away from the observer. This observation was key to Hubble's discovery that the universe is expanding.": "",
  "A research team points a telescope at a nebula and observes bright lines at specific wavelengths against a mostly dark background. Based on Kirchhoff's laws, what type of spectrum are they observing and what does it tell them about the nebula?": "",
  "A reflected spectrum, indicating the nebula is simply reflecting light from a nearby star": "",
  "A continuous spectrum, indicating the nebula is a dense, hot solid": "",
  "An absorption spectrum, indicating cooler gas is blocking background starlight": "",
  "An emission line spectrum, indicating a hot, low-density gas is emitting light at wavelengths characteristic of its chemical elements": "",
  "According to Kirchhoff's third law, bright lines at specific wavelengths against a dark background indicate an emission line spectrum produced by a hot, low-density gas. The specific wavelengths identify the chemical elements present in the nebula.": "",
  "A student measures the hydrogen H-alpha line from a star and finds it at 659.2 nm instead of the laboratory rest wavelength of 656.3 nm. Using the Doppler formula, what can the student determine about the star's motion?": "",
  "The star is approaching Earth because the wavelength is longer than expected": "",
  "The star is rotating but has no radial velocity component": "",
  "The star is receding from Earth because the observed wavelength is longer (redshifted) compared to the rest wavelength": "",
  "The star is stationary because the difference is within measurement error": "",
  "Since the observed wavelength (659.2 nm) is longer than the rest wavelength (656.3 nm), the line is redshifted, meaning the star is moving away from Earth. Using the Doppler formula, the radial velocity can be calculated from the fractional wavelength shift.": "",
  "An astrophysicist examines two stars and finds that Star A's spectrum peaks at 300 nm (ultraviolet) while Star B's spectrum peaks at 700 nm (red). Using Wien's displacement law, what can the astrophysicist conclude?": "",
  "Star A is much hotter than Star B, because a shorter peak wavelength corresponds to a higher surface temperature": "",
  "Both stars have the same temperature but different sizes": "",
  "Star A is cooler than Star B because ultraviolet light carries less energy": "",
  "Star B is hotter because red light has longer wavelengths indicating more total energy": "",
  "Wien's displacement law states that peak wavelength is inversely proportional to temperature. Star A, peaking in the ultraviolet at 300 nm, has a much higher surface temperature than Star B, which peaks in the red at 700 nm, making Star A roughly twice as hot.": "",
  "Astronomers using the JWST observe an exoplanet transiting its host star and compare the star's spectrum during the transit to its spectrum when the planet is not in front of the star. They detect additional absorption features during the transit at wavelengths corresponding to water vapor. What can they conclude?": "",
  "The host star itself contains water vapor in its photosphere": "",
  "The water features come from Earth's own atmosphere contaminating the observations": "",
  "The exoplanet has liquid oceans on its surface reflecting starlight": "",
  "The exoplanet's atmosphere contains water vapor, which imprinted absorption features on the starlight as it passed through the planet's atmosphere during transit": "",
  "Transit spectroscopy works by detecting the additional absorption imprinted by a planet's atmosphere on starlight passing through it. Since the water vapor features appear only during transit and not in the star's normal spectrum, they must originate in the exoplanet's atmosphere.": "",
  "A solar physicist notices that spectral lines from a sunspot region are split into multiple components, while the same lines from a quiet region of the Sun show no splitting. What is the most likely cause of this observation?": "",
  "The sunspot is moving rapidly away from the observer, causing extreme Doppler broadening": "",
  "The sunspot has a different chemical composition than the surrounding photosphere": "",
  "The strong magnetic field in the sunspot is causing the Zeeman effect, splitting the spectral lines": "",
  "The sunspot region is much hotter than the quiet region, causing thermal broadening": "",
  "Sunspots are regions of intense magnetic fields on the Sun's surface. The Zeeman effect causes spectral lines to split into multiple components in the presence of strong magnetic fields, and the degree of splitting reveals the magnetic field strength, which can reach thousands of gauss in sunspots.": "",
  "A team of astrochemists points a radio telescope at a dense molecular cloud and detects emission lines in the microwave and millimeter range. They identify rotational transition lines of carbon monoxide (CO) and water (H2O). Why are radio and millimeter wavelengths used instead of visible light for this observation?": "",
  "Molecular rotational and vibrational transitions emit at radio and infrared wavelengths, and dense clouds are opaque to visible light due to dust": "",
  "Radio telescopes are cheaper and more widely available than optical telescopes": "",
  "Molecules do not interact with visible light at all": "",
  "Visible light telescopes cannot be pointed at molecular clouds due to safety regulations": "",
  "Molecular transitions involving rotation and vibration produce spectral lines at radio, millimeter, and infrared wavelengths rather than visible light. Additionally, dense molecular clouds are filled with dust that absorbs visible light, making radio and millimeter observations essential for studying their chemical composition.": "",
  "An astronomer discovers a new object with an extremely high redshift (z = 6.5) in a deep-field survey. The spectrum shows broad emission lines typical of an active galactic nucleus. What can the astronomer infer about this object?": "",
  "It is a planet in our solar system reflecting sunlight with an unusual spectrum": "",
  "It is a very distant quasar, seen as it existed when the universe was less than a billion years old, with its high redshift caused by the expansion of space": "",
  "It is a nearby star with unusual spectral features being misidentified": "",
  "It is an artificial satellite producing interference in the telescope data": "",
  "An extremely high cosmological redshift of z = 6.5 places this object at an enormous distance, meaning we are seeing it as it was when the universe was less than a billion years old. The broad emission lines of an active galactic nucleus identify it as a quasar, among the most luminous and distant objects ever observed.": "",
  "A graduate student is classifying stars and finds that one star shows very strong hydrogen Balmer lines while another shows prominent molecular absorption bands of titanium oxide (TiO). Based on the OBAFGKM classification system, how should the student classify these stars?": "",
  "Neither can be classified because molecular bands are not part of the classification system": "",
  "The star with strong Balmer lines is likely an A-type star (~10,000 K), while the star with TiO bands is an M-type star (~3,000 K)": "",
  "The star with Balmer lines is an M-type star, while the TiO star is an O-type star": "",
  "Both are O-type stars because they show strong spectral features": "",
  "Hydrogen Balmer lines are strongest in A-type stars at around 10,000 K, where hydrogen atoms are optimally excited to the n=2 level. Titanium oxide (TiO) molecular bands appear only in the coolest M-type stars (~3,000 K), because molecules would be dissociated at higher temperatures.": "",
  "An exoplanet research team detects periodic blueshifts and redshifts in a star's spectral lines with a semi-amplitude of about 1 m/s over a 4.2-day cycle. No brightness variations are detected. What is the most likely explanation, and what technique is being used?": "",
  "An unseen planet is causing a tiny gravitational wobble in the star, detected via the radial velocity (Doppler) method using high-resolution spectroscopy": "",
  "Instrument noise is producing random fluctuations that appear periodic by coincidence": "",
  "The star is a binary system with a companion star pulling it back and forth": "",
  "The star is pulsating, expanding and contracting on a 4.2-day cycle": "",
  "The radial velocity (Doppler wobble) method uses high-resolution spectrographs to detect tiny periodic shifts in a star's spectral lines caused by the gravitational tug of an orbiting planet. A semi-amplitude of ~1 m/s with no brightness changes is characteristic of an exoplanet detection, as binary companions would produce much larger velocity shifts.": ""
}